text: As an actual ADOS NOT supporting this new Harriet Tubman movie at all!    So tired of these non-ADOS Black immigrants (who're mostly Nigerian-British) playing key ADOS historical figures in American film productions.     Folks felt some kind of way with me for me not really liking 12  Years A Slave. Not that Chiwetel Ejiofor or Lupita Nyong'o aren't good actors, but I just didn't/couldn't feel them in the roles they portrayed. I only felt their portrayals in a performative sense and not in a way that convinced me that they WERE the characters. Conversely, when Denzel portrayed Malcolm X, I FELT him as Malcolm.    For example, it's not that a non-Jewish White actor COULDN'T portray or WOULDN'T do a good job portraying a Jewish Holocaust survivor, it's just that, it wouldn't/can't hit the same. Just how deeply could they get into the role? There's just a different kind of energy/spirit that lineage enables.    Not to mention the fact that the Nigerian-British actor they have portraying Harriet Tubman (an ADOS legendary hero) has made anti-ADOS statements all on her Twitter and cosigned anti-ADOS Tweets from other non-ADOS Black immigrants and Whites. Furthermore, I think it's high time we started learning about the lineage of many of these non-ADOS Blacks portraying ADOS historical figures. I mean, I think it'd be an unforgivable insult to have someone, who's ancestors participated in the enslavement of our ancestors, portraying our ancestors.    #LineageMatters #ADOS #AttackOfTheBodySnatchers #HeritageTheft #LineageThieves

Political questions will always be prejudicial, dominant, and all-absorbing. There will be fighting at the door of the Legislative Palace, and the struggle within will be no less furious. To know this, it is hardly necessary to examine what transpires in the French and English legislatures; merely to understand the issue is to know the answer. Is there any need to offer proof that this odious perversion of the law is a perpetual source of hatred and discord; that it tends to destroy society itself? If such proof is needed, look at the United States [in 1850]. There is no country in the world where the law is kept more within its proper domain: the protection of every person's liberty and property. As a consequence of this, there appears to be no country in the world where the social order rests on a firmer foundation. But even in the United States, there are two issues ‚Äî and only two ‚Äî that have always endangered the public peace. Slavery and Tariffs Are Plunder What are these two issues? They are slavery and tariffs. These are the only two issues where, contrary to the general spirit of the republic of the United States, law has assumed the character of a plunderer. Slavery is a violation, by law, of liberty. The protective tariff is a violation, by law, of property. It is a most remarkable fact that this double legal crime ‚Äî a sorrowful inheritance from the Old World ‚Äî should be the only issue which can, and perhaps will, lead to the ruin of the Union. It is indeed impossible to imagine, at the very heart of a society, a more astounding fact than this: The law has come to be an instrument of injustice. text: "She's far and away one of the bravest Americans ever. Most Underground RR operatives were conductors, ushering freed enslaved persons from the border states further north. Tubman was an abductor, returning to the South to rescue people out from slavery. She easily could have been returned to slavery.    Beyond that, Tubman was a nurse, philanthropist, soldier and spy. Late in the war of rebellion she masterminded and led a Union raid on a huge plantation, which the soldiers torched and rescued 750 people.    She was a true American, a true patriot, and a real hero. Get rid of Jackson, the white supremacist slaveholder who caused the deaths of 10,000 Native Americans from the Trail of Tears. Honor Tubman, someone whose legacy surpassed that of pretty much anyone of her time or any other." Larry Witte

text: Her head trauma from childhood caused her to have seizures and blackouts. One such blackout caused for her to collapse and roll off the side of the road while she was first on the run, which helped to hide her from anyone passing by on the road. She would have been spotted and recaptured if she didn't have a blackout at that moment. I know people say it a lot, but it's true that God was with her during her life. Her injury could have cost her her life. Her seizures could have eventually killed her. She could have blacked out at a bad time. She could have been caught at any time during her "conductor" career. But God had a plan for her, and now everyone knows her name and her sacrifices.

text: "The Great Harriet Tubman Was Awesome!"  This trailer is awesome!  I can't wait to see the entire movie!  There is always a connection with our Ancestry to "The Continent (Africa)!"  The great Araminta's (the great Harriet Tubman's birth name), grand mother was arrived in United States on a slave ship.  She was sold to a plantation family named Pattison.  She was given the name "Modesty."  Around 1790, she gave birth to a baby girl, Harriet. She and her family called her "Rit."  The Pattison's called her "Rittia." ( Read "Harriet Tubman: Road To Freedom" by Catherine Clinton, page 5, paragraph 5).  Cynthia Erivo is a preeminent: actress, singer and dancer!  Some people are angry because she got the role instead of an African American actress.  Yet, African American actors have played Africans throughout history...without backlash!  Denzel Washington portrayed the great Steve Biko in "Cry Freedom," Don Cheadle portrayed Paul Rasesabagina in "Hotel Rawanda," Forest Whitaker Idi Amin in "Last King of Scotland," etc.  The best actor or actress is chosen for a role, to bring that character to life!  Most actors and actresses have to audition to get a role.  Some are selected because of their exceptional talents, like Denzel Washington!  Cynthia Erivo is a phenomenal actress!  The film "Harriet" is about telling the great "Harriet Tubman's Story!"  Cynthia Erivo is the vessel whereby this great story will be told!

text: Regarding the hear-say, the rumors...the gossip that abounds on this post, it is unfortunate that we spend so much energy tearing people down!  I am an African American male and hear and see us maliciously putting each other down!  Some of us have even put Africans down too!  It used to me a norm, whereby, if we were called or connected with Africa we would reach a boiling point of anger!  "I am not African!  I have nothing to do with Africa!"  Yet, in all actuality, our enslaved Ancestors, whether taken to: Cuba, Jamaica, South America, North America, England, Australia were from Africa!  And, we, their offspring, are connected to Africa! This is our oneness with each other! I stated this before in my previous post, "Harriet Tubman's grandmother Modesty" arrived in the United States on a slave ship from Africa!  Harriet, though she was born here had that connection to the Continent via her grandmother!  Everyone is entitled to speak their mind and spew whatever non sense that they want to!  However, we will never move forward, come together in any positive way, collectively, until we learn to accept each other, embrace one another, regardless of whether we are African, African American, etc.!  That ultimately extends to the human family too!
author: Maceo Leon Thomas

text: Ms. Harriet Tubman is one of the most patriotic daughters America has ever produced and unlike many legends her legend is true.  She earned the respect of bounty hunters who could not capture her or her keep.  She earned the respect of military officials by accomplishing missions behind enemy lines and returning safely to the other side.  She did all of this in a time when women were regarded as little more than children and enslaved Africans regarded as property. I read about the backlash over the decision to cast Cynthia Erivo as the lead but I have none of those misgivings as I have no reason not to trust Ms. Kasi Lemmons' instincts in this matter. #HARRIET

text: I have friends who are black, some of them are the best people I have ever met! I have a black musician Jimi Hendrix as my profile picture, and there are many more reasons why ‚Äúblack‚Äù and ‚Äúwhite‚Äù are indifferent, and there are great people among all ethnicities and backgrounds, and also terrible people from each as well. But sometimes I really do think, what if slavery didn‚Äôt exist? What if the Europeans had just left the Africans alone for the entire historical era of colonizing America? Hell, even before that, if they didn‚Äôt tie people up like dogs and force labor upon them, anywhere. What difference would it have done? Africa, would still be Africa. I doubt America would have progressed as fast without such a vast amount of free labor, but some of the most terrible things were necessary for the eventual improvement of society; both in terms of direct influence on culture, and the overall moral sensitivity of the globe. Without slavery, America would be all whites/ natives/ Mexicans. Perhaps with the African elite moving over here now, maybe. But think of the opportunity that the black youth now have because of the gradual holcocaust sent forth upon the unwilling Africans. It really is saddening, but the sacrifices forced into life and the ignorant european ambitions gave the African culture a step forward that they would have otherwise completely missed. I‚Äôm not for or against racism or slavery, it doesn‚Äôt concern me. But sometimes I do think about the course of history, and what everything else would be like should it have never happened. Moreover, what aspects of terrorism we can take and be grateful for. Not the typical way to think, but our intelligence is evolving, and I believe that every hideous thing that has happened to this beautiful civilization, was not without reason and just cause for the collective. As a whole, we are better for the shameful acts that we learned from. Be it directly or inderectly, stop subjectifying your own experience, and open your eyes to the objective. Humanity has NEVER done any wrong. Because each and every person has THEIR OWN source of what‚Äôs right, so who can really be ashamed of what they believe? I‚Äôm open to your criticism, though I won‚Äôt care enough to take counsel from it.

text: The real Harriet Tubman sounds more intimidating than this girl. She was struck on the head with a weight, which caused her to behave lethargically. So she probably never had the youthful energy of this actress. She was said to suffer seizures, and narcolepsy as a result. But on TOP of the underground railroad. She allied herself with John Brown to enact a violent uprising that Frederick Douglass wanted no part of. Imagine the fortitude it takes to do things like that, when you could be incapacitated by past brain damage at  *any* point. She would threaten to shoot runaway slaves who tried to head back while she was transporting them north.  Harriet Tubman was a victim of slavery by definition but she wasn't a _victim_ - she looks too vulnerable in this movie.

text: Acc to Wikipedia:   "In 1849, Tubman escaped to Philadelphia, then immediately returned to Maryland to rescue her family. Slowly, one group at a time, she brought relatives with her out of the state, and eventually guided dozens of other slaves to freedom. Traveling by night and in extreme secrecy, Tubman (or "Moses", as she was called) "never lost a passenger".After the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850 was passed, she helped guide fugitives farther north into British North America, and helped newly freed slaves find work. Tubman met John Brown in 1858, and helped him plan and recruit supporters for his 1859 raid on Harpers Ferry.    When the Civil War began, Tubman worked for the Union Army, first as a cook and nurse, and then as an armed scout and spy. The first woman to lead an armed expedition in the war, she guided the raid at Combahee Ferry, which liberated more than 700 slaves."   So, yeah, she was badass.  And way ahead of her time.
author: Tal Benschar

text: I live in south western Ohio, which was the end of the Underground Railroad. We always had southern slave owners come up north and search our houses for slaves. If you walk through the houses on Main Street, there are so many hiding places. There are rumors of Harriet bringing them here a couple times. We had crawl spaces in our basements (my house is old enough to still have one) and the Wright brothers house (yes the guys who invented the plane) had a hollow wall that could fit six people in it. There are even some houses that you can see a little hatch right next to the main doors and they open up to lead to a storage room but they looked a lot like storm hatches so they were never checked. I just think it‚Äôs crazy that my town was the very end of it and we harbored them here and then sent them off to freedom soon after. That to me is amazing.

text: Being a black man mixed with Cherokee heritage . . . . . We all are given the stories of Martin, Malcolm,trail of tears and stories of the men who fought to break the barriers and really shed light on the injustices of people and inequality of treatment. I know in today's society women have been bringing to light the harassment, rapes and harsh treatment they receive for being looked at as nothing more that sex objects in the workplace.  Point is a quote from Janet Jackson rhythm nation album, " In Complete Darkness we are all the same , it is only our knowledge and wisdom that separates us . . . . Dont let your eyes deceive you " . I take great pride in seeing that FINALLY a movie with a strong female of historic proportions, has been made. Not twerking, not about sex, not about using what she got , to get what she wants,  a genuine leader, a faith fueled Queen on a mission to free as many as she could.  We all need to see this movie and REEDUCATE our priorities . Ppl today always complain about frivolous shit, my phone,  my car, my hair , my J's, my house, my status, my my my my my my . Next time you decide to complain about your pampered lifestyle and how your entitled life is so hard,  pick up a book, open ya fucking mind and really embrace the hardships of what Many Many humans had to endure hundreds of years ago for you to enjoy what you have now . I pray this movie changes lives and unifies us all . We all must stand for something . We All Kings and Queens, Masters of Our destinies,  Thank You Harriet

text: the true story is fascinating enough. why does hollywood always change the facts?! they think the true story is not enough?!  harriet never encountered her "slave owner" while on the run & never jumped off a bridge to escape him.  she was loaned out to a neighbor where she would work & her owner would get paid. he wasnt a rich land owner, he inherited his mothers slaves & he was a struggling father of 10 children. thats why he loaned out some of his slaves.  this was a common practice. thats when she fled. so her owner didnt even know she was missing  until 2 weeks went by. she was already across the mason dixon line & long gone by then.  he was in his mid to late 40's when she escaped, not at all the hunky actor they portrayed either.  anyway, these circumstances were lucky for her because they might  have caught her had they known earlier.  she never stated that she was molested or raped.  she was beaten & whipped many times. if you research the records,  & read in tubmans own words, she rescued about 70 people,  mostly family & friends in 13 trips. people she knew. it would have been too dangerous to offer help to strangers.  so why exaggerate the truth?!  what she did is heroic & inspiring to us all. to go back into the enemies territory knowing if caught she would be whipped, beaten, maybe maimed & killed....& did it again & again?!  that is a true hero.  we dont need you to hollywood it up. i havent seen the movie yet but i bet there are more made up parts.  that annoys me. i love history. & its all in the details.

text: Would you believe Araminta/Harriet had a brain injury that she got during adolescence from a cruel slave master, who hit her on the head with a two pound weight¬† causing  her to suffer horrible headaches, epileptic seizures,  she had bouts of falling unconcious and staying out for hours at at time, the older she got the more these episodes increased.  Araminta/Harriet's escape... Her value decreased because of her health issues. Brodress offered a hundred dollar reward if Araminta/Harriet was caught outside Maryland.  If she was caught within the state of Maryland, the reward was fifty dollars.  Araminta/Harriet and her siblings were  "free"  who was actually held captive and regularly beaten by their "owners"... Araminta/Harriet had learned that her¬† mother and father were free due to their indentureship had been fulfilled at age 45... when the "owner" died,  Harriet left and wasn't missed for some time...¬† she was usually hired out to tend to babies/little children of whites in the surrounding area, hunting and gathering game... she'd be gone for weeks at a time.  Description of Araminta/Harriet... very dark skinned, short...five ft. in height, missing two front teeth and petite in body. Araminta/Harriet also had brain surgery performed on her sometime in the 1890s to help alleviate the pain and suffering she was enduring.... nothing in the records show the surgery helped her.  She died in 1913 at the home for the sick, disabled, aged (which she founded) .  Her deeds... According to Tubman‚Äôs own words, and extensive documentation on her rescue missions, we know that¬†she rescued about 70 people ‚Äì family and friends ‚Äì¬† during approximately 13 trips to Maryland and only to Maryland.¬† ¬†During public and private meetings during 1858 and 1859,¬†Tubman repeatedly told people that she had rescued¬†50 to 60 people.¬† This was before her very last mission,¬†in December 1860, when she brought away 7 people.¬† Sarah Bradford exaggerated the numbers in her 1868 biography... where it's given that Harriet helped 300 slaves escape.  Myth:¬†Harriet Tubman carried a rifle on her UGRR rescue missions Fact:¬†Harriet Tubman carried a small¬†pistol¬†with her on her rescue missions, mostly for protection from slave catchers, but also to encourage weak-hearted¬† runaways from turning back and risking the safety of the rest of the group.¬†Tubman carried a sharp-shooters rifle during the Civil War.  Fake Quote:¬†‚ÄúI freed a thousand slaves. I could have freed a thousand more if only they knew they were slaves.‚Äù Original Quote:¬†There is no original quote for this. This quote was entirely made up, and became popularized starting sometime in the the 1990s.¬† There is no documentation, nor historical basis for this quote.  Fake Quote: ‚ÄúEvery great dream begins with a dreamer. Always remember, you have within you the strength, the patience, and the passion to reach for the stars to change the world.‚Äù¬† Original Quote:¬† There is no original quote for this. This quote was entirely made up in 2007.¬† There is no documentation, nor historical basis for this quote.  Fake Quote:¬†‚ÄúChildren, if you are tired, keep going; if you are hungry, keep going; if you want to taste freedom, keep going‚Äù Original Quote:¬†There is no original quote for this. This quote was entirely made up, and became popularized in the 1960s during the Civil Rights Movement.¬†There is no documentation, nor historical basis for this quote.

text: Oh my gosh! Harriet Tubman was my childhood hero. I remember at age 11 going to the library and to the librarian's astonishment checking out an entire stack of books about her from the adult non-fiction section. I even caused a small explosion in my mom's kitchen attempting to make root beer after reading how she would brew it to sell and make money to fund Civil War troops. After reading every piece of material l could find l started thinking how a movie NEEDED to be made about her life and started writing a screenplay myself. Unfortunately I was so set on making it accurate and not missing any details that it ended up longer than the Days of Our Lives series. Lol. Then my friends informed me that, sure the screenplay was good but no one would take it seriously since l was white and it was about a hero of the black community. :-( l am genuinely nervous about the idea of going to see this movie!

text: Amazing they make a movie about her, then again it is Hollywood. She broke the law of the USA by taking slaves (property of their owners) from the United States into Canada even though it was illegal to do so (Fugitive Slave Act of 1850), she did this from 1850-1860 from what I have read. The United States Supreme Court had already ruled that slavery was a constitutional right in the Dred Scott case (1857). New York City draft riots (1863) is also an interesting read. The Civil War (Lincoln‚Äôs War), when taught in schools, does not mention the Morrill Tariff, Corwin‚Äôs Amendment, Taney Arrest Warrant or that during the Civil War the Lincoln Administration and Arbitrary Arrests ‚Äì at least 14,401 civilians were arrested by the Lincoln administration. Or that the Emancipation Proclamation, freed zero slaves? That is right, not even the ones in the Union.       John Brown was another law breaker of the USA. He was defeated by US Marines (1859). He was tried, convicted, and executed by hanging on December 2, 1859, in Charles Town, Virginia. This was of course before any State split from the United States due to the Morrill Tariff and not slavery since remember what I mentioned earlier, the United States Supreme Court had already ruled that slavery was a constitutional right in the Dred Scott case (1857).      If any of my statements on here are wrong, please post some links so I can read them.

text: Here is why i think this might be great. Most Americans think the South was the cruel place, and the north was a "heaven" for black people. In reality, everywhere kinda sucked. After the Civil War, many blacks moved north in hopes of "getting away" from hatred. The reality is that the north wasn't exactly "fans" of black people either. Lincoln himself didnt really care about slavery during the Civil War. A quote from him: "If i can win the war by freeing the slaves, i would do it. If i can win the war without freeing the slaves, i would do it." Lincoln only cared when he realized the political advantage of it. Britain and France was very close to assisting the Confederacy in 1861 and 1862. Lincoln announced the Proclamation STRICTLY because it would make the British and French back out (since they already abolished slavery before the war.) So for anyone out there who is black, realize the Proclamation wasn't really because Lincoln cared. It was more for political/winning the war purposes.

text: Just so you know, the rest of the world thinks this whole obsession that Americans have with slavery (both black and white people) is both disturbing and a little pathetic. It's actually kind of comical how hard filmmakers pander to the black community these days and it's even funnier how the black community just eats it up like a stupid little fat kid.    There's a reason why no other nation on Earth obsesses over their histories of enslavement like Americans do, and that's because you all _don't want to_ get over slavery. You want to keep being victims because that's your whole identity at this point and it's become a way of life, complete with its own little consumerist economy and media to back it up.   But even more than that, you don't want to be truly free because that would mean you'd have to find something else to justify your existence apart from 'the good fight' against 'your oppressors'. And maybe that's why white and Asian people keep doing so much better in life than black people: because they're not busy 'struggling' against some imaginary enemy and that gives them time to  focus on actual problems like not having enough money. Just saying.

text: There's only been one movie made about the Little Rock Nine, and that was based on the journal of the principal, a white woman, at the school, and the movie was made after she died.  I don't know how much names were changed in the movie, but I have often felt if that was something involving nine white American children in the 1950s, or eight white and one "non-white", there would have been a movie made about what they endured every 12 to 15 years coming out of Hollywood.  There must be something to do with permission, because Spike Lee made a movie about the four girls killed in the Alabama church, and I'm really surprised he hasn't opted to make a movie about the Little Rock Nine.  I know one of the kids has passed away, but that has always been the way Hollywood does it, so they don't have to pay out royalities; they wait for everyone involved to die.  But this movie comes near forty years after the tv miniseries with Cicely Tyson, and that is generally also how Hollywood does it; usually the copyright or something is up every thirty years, but this one was clearly stretched to forty.  Well, it seems the Disney channel had a movie about Ernest Greene the first of the Little Rock Nine to graduate from the school, but I've never seen that, and don't recall hearing much about it.

text: Saw the film and Cynthia Erivo's searing performance should put the naysayer's objections to bed. She commanded the screen and portrayed Tubman with a keen ferocity. Erivo brilliantly conveyed Harriet's vulnerabilities, as well as her strength, focus and determination. What I also  liked was the story focused primarily on how Tubman became a legend, and it didn't show the overused images of the brutalities of slavery, we already know that slavery  was HELL. But what this film did do is show a people who wanted to be free, and Tubman's resolve to make that happen, even if it meant risking her own life and freedom.

text: This is ultimately owned by Comcast, a company currently headed to the Supreme Court on Nov 13th to override the Civil Rights Act of 1866, laws put on the books to protect the very people depicted in this movie??? Come the hell on!! *You all just like symbolism and representation at any cost. Even you own damn civil rights!* You do understand that if Comcast wins this case, we will no longer be able to file suit against companies and institutions that discriminate on the basis of race?? We would have to prove that the ONLY reason they turned us away is race, something nearly impossible to do.  That is my main reason for not supporting this film, I will never enrich the company fighting against my rights and my ancestors' legacy. But on top of all of that, the movie was grossly inaccurate. The character Bigger Long never existed, you know why? *Because there were NO black bounty hunters trying to catch runaway slaves in the history of this country!* How disgusting do you have to be to ignore the actual historical data (like that in which Harriet was attacked by her former owner, resulting in her having seizures and hallucinations for the rest of her life, NOT paranormal superhero powers like depicted in the film) and make a black main the primary villain in this movie??? Harriet also never had a friend that was murdered by a black bounty hunter, so that whole scene was just to further the cause of making the audience hate him. A white woman on Twitter spoke about taking her 11 year old to see the film and her leaving, saying she was afraid of black men!! We won't even touch on the sick sexual innuendos made by his name, or the fact he will use the money from catching Harriet to "Buy enough white whores to last him to Atlanta". This movie furthers the gender wars sentiments that are currently tearing the community apart. *This is the representation you want??????*  You all are either terribly uninformed, or agents of chaos to support this film. Erivo has made disgusting comments about black Americans, but I should disregard all of the points above because she has melanin in her skin? Miss me with that gaslighting bs.

text: Initially, I was very happy to hear that a movie was going to made about one of the most important and prominent historical figures in our history. But I was quickly disappointed to learn that the movie was a mere reflection of falsifications from the imaginations of the writers, producers and directors, as oppose to their relying on the evidence of pure historical facts. All the while resting on traditional racial prejudicial narratives against Black men, with arguably the most violent person in the movie being a bounty hunter i.e. "slave tracker", who was Black (and a historically non-existent, invented character),  who tried to capture the character Harriet, for her return to slavery, and then tries to kill her near the movie's end. But his attempt was stopped in the nick of time by Harriet's former White slave owner, also an invented character, who saves Harriet's life. The aforementioned is only a portion of the lies in this movie, and there was not a void of the many levels of fiction and historical inconsistencies. While they were at it, had the writers thought to make the character Harriet played by a White woman, she would not have been in strange company, given the many liberties the writers took in making the numerous fictitious characters and story lines that came to play with the central star of the film. At the conclusion of the movie, a patron in the theater loudly exclaimed words along the lines of, "You teenagers need to go and write a book report !!!" People responded in laughter. Had any of the teenagers taken this advise from this older patron, and had done a book report solely on the content of this movie, they would have undoubtedly received an "F", if the report were to be graded only on the merit of historical facts regarding Harriet Tubman's life. So, here is what I would suggest: Teenagers, this film's portrayal of Harriet Tubman'd life is highly fictionalize, and has some elements of truth that is exceptionally marginal in comparison to what is not true. Sadly to say, you may find Wikipedia a more credible resource, or might lead you to more credible resources. I would suggest for your book report, that you obtain your information about Harriet Tubman's life from non-fiction books,  records, and qualified historians of Black American history, and Harriet Tubman's life in particular.  Most importantly,  make sure that you do your due diligence in verifying the correctness of the information you learn.

text: The only reward for Tubman‚Äôs capture is in the October 3, 1849 advertisement for the return of ‚ÄúMinty‚Äù and her brothers ‚ÄúBen‚Äù and ‚ÄúHarry,‚Äù in which their mistress, Eliza Brodess, offered $100 for each of them if caught outside of Maryland.  Slaveholders on the Eastern Shore of Maryland had no idea it was Harriet Tubman (or, Minty Ross, as they knew her) who was helping and inspiring people to run away.  The $40,000 bounty figure was made up by Sallie Holley, a former anti-slavery activist in New York, who wrote a letter to a newspaper in 1867, arguing for support for Tubman in her pursuit of back pay and pension from the Union Army.

text: "Oh my God. Why?  Look, nobody's questioning Harriet Tubman's contributions or her role in the history of the abolitionist movement. But, except for the names, this movie has about as much to do with actual history as Underdog does with rescuing war dogs. I have to wonder what would have happened to a black woman walking around in the slave holding south dressed like Hollywood's version of a pseudo Annie Oakley. The filmmakers had a golden opportunity here to get this right but chose to throw a bunch of candified, Hollywood cliches at it instead. That's not to say there weren't some emotional moments, but the real history and achievement of Harriet Tubman is emotional and soul stirring enough without burying it under 10 feet of Hollywood glitz in order to appeal to the superhero crowd. Boo. Hiss."                                                                                                                                                                                         - Random Internet Review

text: This was an excellent movie! I have been a fan of Harriet Tubman since I first learned of her in grade school. And I am white. When I saw that a movie was coming out about her, I couldn't wait to see it. But I didn't want to see it at the theater because of being white and not knowing if anger at white people would be directed at me. So, I waited for the movie to come out on DVD. Loved this movie so much! Harriet Tubman was one tough lady. They just don't make people like her anymore. We are all consumed with selfishness. She risked her life to save her people. Never lost one person. And when she needed surgery on her brain to relieve the pain she had experienced for years after being beaten by her owner, she didn't have anesthesia. She instead bit down on a bullet. If only I had an ounce of her strength and courage, I would be so very thankful.
